    <item id="n9Cr4BPjkMA" expanded="yes">
      <values>
        <text>
          <p>
            <run>
              <lit>User Profile</lit>
            </run>
          </p>
        </text>
      </values>
      <children>
        <item id="e1ORRrwh7-r">
          <values>
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>Electronic Musicians who use samples of instruments or recordings from one part of a song, such as a rhythm break, to construct another song of their own.  These samples are typically in the </lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit><cell href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WAV" name="Waveform Audio" type="link"/></lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit> (.wav) or </lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit><cell href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Audio_Interchange_File_Format" name="Audio Interchange" type="link"/></lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit> (.aiff) file formats, but there are also proprietary formats from companies, such as </lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit><cell href="http://www.native-instruments.com/en/" name="Native Instruments" type="link"/></lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit> and </lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit><cell href="https://www.ableton.com/" name="Ableton" type="link"/></lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit>.</lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </values>
        </item>
      </children>
    </item>
    <item id="dGp5itjrhX2" expanded="yes">
      <values>
        <text>
          <p>
            <run>
              <lit>Use case</lit>
            </run>
          </p>
        </text>
      </values>
      <children>
        <item id="puz9hDMX0Kx">
          <values>
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>An electronic musician may utilize hundred’s of samples for just one song.  As she creates more music, she will acquire more and more original samples and will often modify her existing samples to suit a new project by changing the pitch, length, or beats per minute (BPM). Unless a musician is extremely well organized, searching for and previewing samples becomes difficult with every new project, creating friction that interferes with their creative flow.</lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </values>
        </item>
      </children>
    </item>
    <item id="mtW3QyHQbwO" expanded="yes">
      <values>
        <text>
          <p>
            <run>
              <lit>Problem space</lit>
            </run>
          </p>
        </text>
      </values>
      <children>
        <item id="a5xs9zuYZuu">
          <values>
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>There is no definitive application that will organize samples from multiple vendors and sources into a system where a musician can efficiently navigate, find, preview and store their samples.  Thus solutions to this problem have been adhoc.  Applications that exist are typically proprietary, and/or tied to a specific vendor’s hardware (see  </lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit><cell href="http://www.native-instruments.com/en/support/knowledge-base/show/794/how-can-i-add-a-sample-library-to-kontakt/" name="How Can I Add a Sample Library to KONTAKT?" type="link"/></lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit> ). Therefore, musicians will typically come up with their </lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit><cell href="https://www.gearslutz.com/board/rap-hip-hop-engineering-production/375245-efficient-ways-organize-your-samples-either-your-computer-your-brain.html" name="own schema" type="link"/></lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit> for categorizing and later navigating through thousands of samples.   There should be a better way to discover, categorize</lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <style>
                    <value key="font-family">Helvetica</value>
                    <value key="font-size">12</value>
                  </style>
                  <lit>, </lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit>organize, search, and preview samples for a recording project that isn&apos;t tied to a specific vendor or hardware.</lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </values>
        </item>
      </children>
    </item>
    <item id="jFxB6FRRjWo" expanded="yes">
      <values>
        <text>
          <p>
            <run>
              <lit>What is my app and how does it help them?</lit>
            </run>
          </p>
        </text>
      </values>
      <children>
        <item id="hj1-U_oSCWv">
          <values>
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>Sampletopia is a browser based app that enables the electronic musician to quickly search, navigate, and preview samples for upcoming recording projects.  A musician’s entire collection of samples is represented as a visual atlas that convey’s the most important information: the information that a musician deems most meaningful to them for finding, previewing and ultimately selecting a sample for a recording.</lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </values>
        </item>
        <item id="d1cIhP5ntb3">
          <values>
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>Naturally it is </lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <style>
                    <value key="underline-style">single</value>
                  </style>
                  <lit>not</lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit> possible to develop a complete application for solving this problem in the week allotted for this project.  Thus, I’m looking at this project as an opportunity to mock up some of the smaller parts to this problem - in particular the navigation through and preview (i.e., listening) of samples.  Depending on outcomes, I may pursue developing a full fledged application on my own time in the future.  </lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </values>
        </item>
        <item id="k4yIOcSPBUw">
          <values>
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>For navigation and preview (i.e., listening), I will start with a simple four paned navigation window that enables the musician to drill down until they have reach a sample they are looking for. Once found, the sample will begin to play and possibly loop until the musician begins searching for another sample.  Information about the sample, including its file format, and location on the hard drive will be presented as well.  As a stretch goal, I would like to experiment with representing the sample library as a graph visualization or atlas.  This would be much more visually appealing and provides additional visual cues (e.g., pictures of the sampled instrument) for the musician to quickly find and preview a sample.</lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </values>
        </item>
        <item id="gwfXSfco3Ps">
          <values>
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>The sample library will be manually curated and preloaded into a database that represents a typical user.  There is no ability to add or delete samples from the library and these samples will be limited to the WAV and AIFF file formats, only.  Note that the actual sample is not stored in the database, but rather a reference to the sample on their hard drive along with meta data that helps to characterize the instrument sampled, and its genre, pitch, etc. </lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </values>
        </item>
      </children>
    </item>
    <item id="bur75eYnPWd" expanded="yes">
      <values>
        <text>
          <p>
            <run>
              <lit>Features</lit>
            </run>
          </p>
        </text>
      </values>
      <children>
        <item id="mWH2tq4uvTt">
          <values>
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>When a musician comes to Sample Atlas, they are presented with a login page.  A musician sample library is often proprietary and thus it should be protected from other users.</lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </values>
          <note expanded="yes">
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>There is no ability to create a library from scratch in this first implementation, and therefore it doesn&apos;t make sense to allow an user to sign up.</lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </note>
        </item>
        <item id="e9TROc9y7RX">
          <values>
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>The musician is presented with visual representation of their sample library.  Then, the musician can immediately begin navigating through categories that make up their library until they come to an endpoint that represents the actual sample.  If they like the sample, they can add it to their “project sheet” for later reference.</lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </values>
          <note expanded="yes">
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>How does this help them?</lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </note>
        </item>
        <item id="cZo9cFhVQbZ">
          <values>
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>At any time, the musician has the option to create a “sample sheet” that allows them to compile a list of samples they may want to use for their project.  This sample sheet is stored with the user, </lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </values>
        </item>
        <item id="lKClLl1YQJJ">
          <values>
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>Once the musician reaches an endpoint, the sample begins playing and all the meta data associated with that sample is presented in the browser. How does each feature help them?</lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </values>
        </item>
        <item id="hc2RBUQsx7A">
          <values>
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>The musician is able to check </lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </values>
        </item>
      </children>
    </item>
    <item id="mXvsXgY_Dhp" expanded="yes">
      <values>
        <text>
          <p>
            <run>
              <lit>What APIs and Frameworks will I be using?</lit>
            </run>
          </p>
        </text>
      </values>
      <children>
        <item id="dfaM2nYCXJJ">
          <values>
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>This project will utilize the majority of concepts and frameworks that we have covered thus far.  In particular, Node, Express, Mongo, and Mongoose will serve as the backend for storing a user’s login, profile, sample sheet, and references to samples that exist on their hard drive. </lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </values>
        </item>
        <item id="iMt2bUq5yBS">
          <values>
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit> I will use the </lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit><cell href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Web_Audio_API" name="Web Audio API" type="link"/></lit>
                </run>
                <run>
                  <lit>  to play back the sample.</lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </values>
        </item>
        <item id="mZlQwJOO4yL">
          <values>
            <text>
              <p>
                <run>
                  <lit>The library will be organized and categorized with the root instrument (e.g., Bass), followed by its type (e.g., Analog Bass), followed by its Mode (e.g., Processed), followed by the actual sample</lit>
                </run>
              </p>
            </text>
          </values>
        </item>
      </children>
    </item>
